---
// "Inverting the record" — Munger's invert-always-invert turned into a checklist. Instead of
// asking why this is a good business, it asks what would make owning it a mistake, and looks
// for those marks in the record the pipeline already holds. Each test is flagged (the
// fingerprint is present, a question to put to the filing) or clear (one fewer way to be
// wrong). No score on the business, only the count of which disconfirming tests fired.
import { inversionChecks } from "../lib/inversion.mjs";

const { company } = Astro.props;
const inv = inversionChecks(company);

// Split the panel: the flags get the full read (the questions inversion actually surfaced), the
// clean tests collapse to a compact "checked and clear" line. The section's job is to show what
// inverting TURNED UP, not to re-list every figure already on the page through a darker frame.
const flagged = inv ? inv.checks.filter((c) => c.flagged) : [];
const clear = inv ? inv.checks.filter((c) => !c.flagged) : [];

// A plain, descriptive read of the tally, never a grade: it counts which tests fired, not
// how good or bad the stock is.
let tally = null;
if (inv) {
  const f = inv.flaggedCount, n = inv.total;
  if (f === 0) tally = `None of the ${n} tests turned up a mark; each came back clean. That is not a verdict that the business is cheap or safe, only that these particular ways of being wrong are not written into the record.`;
  else if (f === n) tally = `All ${n} tests turned up something to look into. Each is a question for the filing, not an answer, but a record that trips every wire is one to understand slowly.`;
  else tally = `${f} of the ${n} tests turned up something to look into; the other ${n - f} came back clean. A flag is a question to put to the filing, not a verdict.`;
}
---

{inv ? (
  <section class="inv">
    <div class="head"><h3 class="secTitle">Inverting the record</h3></div>
    <p class="lede">
      Munger's rule was to <b>invert</b>: don't ask why {company.name || company.ticker} is a good business,
      ask what would make owning it a mistake, then look for those marks in the record. These are the
      disconfirming tests across {inv.span}. A flag points at a question; it is never a verdict.
    </p>

    <p class="tally">{tally}</p>

    {flagged.length ? (
      <ul class="checks">
        {flagged.map((c) => (
          <li class="flag">
            <div class="crow">
              <span class="chip">Look here</span>
              <span class="clabel">{c.label}</span>
              <span class="cvalue">{c.value}</span>
            </div>
            <p class="cnote">{c.note}</p>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    ) : null}

    {clear.length ? (
      <div class="clears">
        <span class="clearsHd">{flagged.length ? "And these came back clean" : "Each test came back clean"}</span>
        <ul class="clearList">
          {clear.map((c) => <li>{c.label}</li>)}
        </ul>
      </div>
    ) : null}

    <p class="foot">
      Each test is read straight from the filings and is noisy on its own; a single flag can be a cyclical
      trough, a year of heavy investment, or a one-off as easily as a problem, which is why each sends you to
      the filing rather than answering for it. None of this scores the business or the price. A clean panel is
      not a reason to buy, and a flagged one is not a reason to sell; both are just the record, inverted.
    </p>
  </section>
) : null}

<style>
  .inv { margin: 24px 0; }
  .head { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-strong); padding-bottom: 6px; }
  .head h2 { margin: 0; }
  .lede { font-family: var(--serif); font-size: clamp(15px, 2.3vw, 17px); line-height: 1.5; margin: 12px 0 0; max-width: 72ch; }
  .lede b { font-weight: 600; }
  .tally { font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--ink-soft); margin: 10px 0 0; max-width: 74ch; line-height: 1.55; }

  .checks { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 16px 0 0; }
  .checks li { padding: 13px 0 13px 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule); border-left: 2px solid transparent; }
  .checks li:first-child { border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); }
  .checks li.flag { border-left-color: var(--warn); }
  .checks li.clear { border-left-color: var(--rule-strong); }

  .crow { display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 12px; }
  .chip { flex: 0 0 auto; font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.05em; text-transform: uppercase; padding: 2px 7px; border: 1px solid currentColor; }
  .flag .chip { color: var(--warn); }
  .clear .chip { color: var(--muted); }
  .clabel { font-weight: 600; font-size: 15px; color: var(--ink); flex: 1 1 auto; }
  .cvalue { font-size: 17px; font-weight: 700; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; flex: 0 0 auto; letter-spacing: -0.01em; color: var(--ink); }

  .cnote { font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--ink-dim); margin: 6px 0 0; line-height: 1.55; max-width: 78ch; }

  /* The clean tests, collapsed: what was checked and came back clear, named without re-listing the
     full read of each (those figures live in the record, the scorecard, and the capital section). */
  .clears { margin: 18px 0 0; padding: 12px 0 4px 12px; border-top: 1px solid var(--rule); border-left: 2px solid var(--rule-strong); }
  .clearsHd { font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 10px; font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.06em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--muted); }
  .clearList { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 10px 0 0; display: grid; gap: 8px; }
  .clearList li { position: relative; padding-left: 19px; font-size: 13.5px; line-height: 1.4; color: var(--ink-dim); }
  .clearList li::before { content: "✓"; position: absolute; left: 0; top: 0; color: var(--muted); font-size: 12px; }

  .foot { font-family: var(--serif); font-style: italic; font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--muted); border-top: 1px solid var(--rule-strong); margin-top: 14px; padding-top: 11px; max-width: 74ch; line-height: 1.5; }

  @media (max-width: 520px) {
    .crow { flex-wrap: wrap; }
    .cvalue { order: 3; flex-basis: 100%; }
  }
</style>
